                                            <div type="positioning"/>
                                            <div type="typology">
                                                <p>Arabia › Northern Group › Syro-Mesopotamian fringe</p>
                                                <p>Bedouin dialect, minority variety</p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="general">
                                                <p>Because the official language of the region is Turkish, the Arabic 
dialect of the city of Urfa is a minority language. Similar varieties of Arabic are 
spoken in many villages and smaller towns (e.g. Harran and Akçakale) situated between 
Urfa and the Syrian border. Urfa Arabic is linguistically very close to the dialects 
of the sheep and goat breeding nomads (the so-called Shawāya) of the Syrian Steppe and 
arguably constitutes the northernmost variety of the Arabian Bedouin dialects. Tribal 
structures among the local Arabic speakers (estimated to be around 150,000) are still 
very strong, and the relatively strict endogamy results in a high proportion of first 
language speakers even among the youngest generation. Urfa Arabic is usually not 
written; but there are internet sites containing phrases, songs, and proverbs in 
vernacular Arabic written in Latin script.</p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="researchHistory">
                                                <p>Although the existence of Arabic speaking groups in the region has 
been known since at least the 19th century, the dialect is still poorly documented. 
A very short grammatical sketch is Procházka 2003, three texts with English translation 
are found in Procházka 2013, and a comparison of Urfa Arabic with other peripheral 
dialects of the region is Procházka 2006.</p>
                                            </div>
